I keep coming back to this vid so here are some tips: -Write down all of these pieces, like a list, then check off all the things you already own, i.e. you might already have a white tee and some black boots but you're missing white sneakers and brallettes. -Customize! Customize! Customize! While some of the stuff in this vid are obviously good to have, like a good pair of jeans, some stuff might not work along with your style in the way you want them to. Normal black boots don't fit into my style super well, but mary janes and loafers do, and they are based on the same idea without being the exact same. Just finding mods to the list that work for you. I added separat points for good jeans WITH rips/holes and one WITHOUT rips/holes, because I love jeans with a distressed look.  -piggy backing off the last point, add stuff! Do you LOVE a good skirt? Do you wear hoodies twice a week? Then, add these things! I personally added a good pair of leggings, a pleated skirt, both simple and patterned, fun sneakers, a good backpack, and several other things that i found essential. -Don't be afraid to get multiple of the same item in diff colours. If you're working with a smaller wardrobe, it's often easier if you have a strict colour pallet. Maybe your thing is white, black, and beige. You find a top in white and you can envision 10 outfits with that top. If you get it in black aswell, suddenly you have 10 more outfits. This is also a great way of outfit repeating without actually outfit repeating. -when looking for fits and styles, don't look at what you're "supposed" to like, look at what you actually like. Just because low rise flare jeans are trendig rn does not mean I will be wearing them. Just because something looks good on someone else doesn't mean it'll look the same on you

protip for everyone who is between 10-14(ish??)! you are still growing!! you can end up growing from things you fit two weeks ago. buy your clothes a size or two big if you can!!! my style is REALLY difrent from when i was in 5-6th grade, then i was like idrc i just buy something from the girls section in the child part of h&m that doesnâ€™t look TO girly (yes thatâ€™s exactly how i would explain it.)and now itâ€™s a mix of oversized baggy alt/grunge/skater/idfk cause style names are apparently a sensitive topic atm, but even tho iâ€™m so much taller then i was in 6th grade(im in 9th grade rn) i can still use a a lot of the clothes because it still fits. obviously there are a lot i donâ€™t use because of the patterns and colours, but the clothes with plain arms and a lot of the hoodies i can wear underneath my oversized t-shirtâ€™s. a lot of the clothes i used to wear are really comfortable so i wear them around the house. i use some when i need to wear something iâ€™m not scared of (like when iâ€™m painting) and that is all because a lot of them still fits. (there are obv a lot that is to small tho donâ€™t get me wrong here)  also kids, while your feet is growing, never buy a lot of pretty expensive shoes. just buy a pair of athletic shoes for summer, a pair of wintershoes that is water and cold/snow proof, maybe a pair of nice shoes for when thatâ€™s needed. +shoes for activities you need special shoes for (or whatever fits your day to day life) thatâ€™s what i did, i picked shoes that i could use, not many expensive shoes that i needed to be careful with. i always had one pair of summer running athletic shoes that i could run outside and play with without being scared(most in black) and a pair of wintershoes+ soccer and ski shoes.   the same with jackets.   only now that iâ€™m pretty sure my feet has stopped growing i have bought shoes to style.  and winter jackets i just have one thicker black i like, and a thinner black.  please be careful when spending money on clothes when your still growing. i still buy a bunch of cheap clothes, because i know iâ€™ll either grow out of the size, or the style.

For my fellas, here are some alternatives to some. I know not everyone is comfortable wearing dresses and heels and there's nothing wrong with wearing them, but these are just some options instead if you don't like heels or dresses. These are pretty much all unisex clothes so feel free to try these too if you're a girl.  Here they are:   Instead of a Nude Heel, get a nice pair of dress shoes. The color depends on what you normally wear but I would mostly recommend a brown dress shoe in an Oxford style but you can mix it up and get a Wingtip or Double Monk, etc. style too if you're adventurous.   I know that the chunky sweater she shows in the video may not be right for you for a variety of reasons. Try maybe an Aran Knit Sweater (beware though, they're itchy) in grey or cream.  Instead of the summer dress, you could instead get a loud short-sleeved dress shirt. Pattern is up to you but I recommend a floral or striped print.  The purse I guess just get a nice satchel or bag in your preferred style like a knapsack or something, whatever goes with your style.

Best advice: 2nd hand shops and charity shops > "vintage" shops for actual budget prices. Vintage shops have caught onto the vintage hype and re-sell even contemporary (H&M, ASOS) clothes as "vintage". I've gotten FILA's, NIKE's and even Dr. Martens for 1/4 of their retail price and practically new in dingy 2nd hand shops rather than cool vintage shops. Kilo sale vintage can also work well on a budget if you mostly select light weight fabrics. At least thats how me and my friends managed to get pretty much everything we wanted on an unemployed highschooler's budget lol

Remember: there are no essentials in a closet that works for everyone. You can take this video as inspiration, but do not take it as facts. Your essentials should be what YOU wear the most. Maybe a pair of yellow pants and a neon shirt is your essentials. If so, it is important that you have them in your closet instead of filling up it with things you should have. My essentials is bright blue mom jeans and a black oversized hoodie, among other things. But I have a black mini skirt in my closet that Iâ€™ve had for years and only wore once. I'm coming back 4 months after watching this video to share a PSA: EXPENSIVE JEANS ARE NOTICEABLE! I never cared too much about jeans because they're expensive as heck, but after I got smarter with shopping I'm never going back. I've never bought an expensive pair of jeans for full price but thanks to depop I have 4 pairs of vintage and/or name brand 100% cotton jeans and since then my jean radar has been beeping. I don't know how, but I really notice jeans in an outfit now. Even when browsing on depop I can tell whether or not jeans are good quality or not just from the picture. And that means I notice on the daily with people I meet, too. Obviously it doesn't matter in the long run if people have good jeans on or not, but good jeans do stand out. I've become more confident when I wear jeans because I know they fit well and look good. I really agree with Ashley that a good pair of jeans changes the whole game. But if you don't have the $100 to spend and your thrift store is an abyss of grandpa clothes, definitely try depop, there's so much selection.

For the people who can't afford them! You can get some cute clothes at Wal-mart/Target and get your accent pieces (Jackets, shoes, overalls, shorts, maybe jeans if you need to)from somewhere else and that saves you money! I do this and most people don't even think that I got my clothes from Wal-mart.

Everything mentioned:  Denim jeans â€” 5% spandex max. The rest is cotton. 100% cotton is also recommended. Skinny jeans can be uncomfortable, go for a straight cut if you prefer more mobility. Ankle length is preferred. Jeans with a raw hem are easy to alter if they are too long.   Denim Shorts â€” Same material as jeans, buy distressed jeans a bit longer as they will shrink in length as the distressed part moves up. Buy a size up if you want more length.   Black boots â€” Doc martins are a good choice. If getting heeled boots get a block heel. Square toe is preferred over round toe. Get boots a bit more form fitting around ankle rather than one with a loose ankle.  White sneakers â€” Solid white is preferred due to versatility, chunky/thicker soled shoes are good.  Nude heels â€” Pointed toe is preferred, block heels recommended due to walking.  Bras â€” VICTORIA SECRET SUCKS!! Lace bras work if itâ€™s gonna be seen. Calvin Klein works too.  T-Shirts â€” Solid white and solid black t-shirts. Try on a ton and pay attention to details. 100% cotton, you can go a size up  White blouse - Details to make it elevated so you can pair it.  Black turtleneck â€” High versatile, good for layering, body suit is good so you can tuck it.   Sweater â€” Crew necks are boring, thrifting is good, 100% silk or cashmere  Pattern dress â€” New little black dress, good fit, get a good zipper, strap dresses work for layering  Denim jacket â€” Can find one at thrift store,  if not in womenâ€™s check mens, plain ones work well  Leather jacket â€” Larger/ dolman sleeve allow for more arm mobility, check hardware  Black purse â€” leather works, interesting hardware, easy to open, easy to wear, easy to close

hi i know i'm really late to this but! i wanna share some ways you can always try to make money or find affordable clothes. i have seen a few people replying to your comment with the same ideas but they could really help. first with finding affordable clothes: alwayssss look for sales!! whether they're from magazines, online store codes, youtube promo codes or sales in stores... always look for sales. with youtube promo codes you can just search the store you want the code for, maybe throw in the word 'haul' and 'promo code' & the current year, you should be able to find something ;) some affordable clothing websites:  boohoo - cute shoes and accessories for very affordable prices. and actually right now, they have a sale online which is GREAT!! believe it's like 60% off women's clothes which is awesome.  pull & bear - uk brand i believe and deliver to US but great quality clothes and fairly priced.  primark - another uk brand, also deliver to US, they have stores on the east coast. for the online store in the US they don't have as many options but its still very affordable and great quality. i love their bathing suits. romwe/shein - if you are looking for very inexpensive clothes, these websites are great. sometimes the material of the clothes can be a little cheap and necessarily look like the picture but i mean, you get what you pay for haha forever 21 - always a great place to look for basics and occasionally some cute pieces hollister - if you are tall like me, they have great skinny jeans that you can find only online i believe. but! they have the option for them to come in a tall size which i love. they usually have sales going on too.  pacsun - they usually have sales or deals going on. super cute tops and shorts.  urban outfitters - if you are looking for more trendy clothes this store has it all but it can be veryyyy expensive. i recommend going to the sale section or always looking for deals.  & finally you can always thrift!! if you go and don't find anything you love, don't feel discouraged!!! go back another day or try a different thrift store bc they are always getting donations and they have new things everyday so don't lose hope! keep looking. also look through everything! even in different sections than you normally would look. it's worth a shot. you can always alter the clothes you thrifted too! there are so many other great, affordable stores. these are just some off the top of my head. but i can't stress enough how important and underrated sales are! don't ignore the annoying popups for a certain percent off on online stores! use them!! now some ways to make money: babysit - make sure you know the parents and have a mutual trust. that is important do chores around the house - ask if your parents/guardians can compensate and give you a little bit of an allowance in return!  ask neighbors (elderly or young with young children) if you can help with any work around the house and/or yard - even if they don't offer to pay you, showing some neighborly love always makes someone and yourself feel good. start a little dog walking business - good exercise and who doesn't love dogs! sell some of your clothes online finally you can  collect shoes from neighbors and family to donate to angelbins - this is great because they pay you by the pound in return for your shoes. i'm not sure how much they pay so it would be great to look into. but the heavier the better! i'm so sorry this is soooo wordy but i wanted to help the best i can with as much detail as possible.  i hope this helps!!!  xoxo, julia <3

Notes for me:  Jeans - high rise make your torso look short - tight-ish - ankle length so cut it or roll - stiff denim lasts longer - no more than 5% spandex    Denim shorts - size a little up so you can breathe - super short shorts draw attention to your thighs and figure - mid way shorts should fit your legs   Black boots - square toe is 70s - ankle area should hug the ankle so it doesnt take away from outfit - stitching    White sneaker - nike air force 1 - look for good stitching - can be paired with actually anything   Heels - neutral so leg looks longer - dont walk in grass with a thin heel - steve maddens  Bras - victoria secret sucks - calvin klein - elastic can work just as well as underwire - dont wear the wrong size   Black White T shirts - sleeves on arms change look - shoulders drape - pair with blue shorts or jeans   White Blouse - show off colar bone - show a little skin but keep it professional too  Black turtleneck - pair with everything - easy to layer - wear big necklaces over it and earrings   Sweater - no crew necks they are boring - no pilling so try not to wash it too often   Dress - a good fit - high quality zipper - draw attention up - collared dresses bring the attention there  Denim Jacket - try find a plain wash - contrast stitching is cute - over size - be mobile in it - avoid a black leather jacket over black   Leather Jacket - the way the sleeve fits to move easy - length so it keeps your figure - hardware should be neutral   Black purse - hardware should match your shoes - high quality material - keep simply accents   This is just for me

!Wardrobe essentials!  Jeans: Go for High rise jeans make sure it ends at the ankles  Raw hems can be cut to fit^ Get stiff denim (100% cotton, 95% cotton 5% spandex)  Denim shorts: Look for high waisted, sometimes a size bigger for room (not so short because they can ride up with age anyways) Nineties shorts are a more conservative look    Black boots: Dr martens  Heel booties (block heels for comfort) ^make sure itâ€™s tight around the ankles Choke boots   White sneakers: Nike airforce one jesters Fila disruptors  Vintage Reeboks   Nude block heels: (Pointed toe, block heel, nude color) Can find these types of shoes at: Steve maddens  Topshop   Bra: Aerie bralette  Calvin Klein   Black and white tees: Make sure that you try on a lot, and come out with the ones that flatter you the most. Go for 100% cotton, and make sure it fits you okay  (You can get a size bigger for a comfortable look)  White blouse: Find one that has small details, to make it look fancy  Black turtleneck: Good for layering, and can go with a lot  Sweater: Go for 100% silk, or 100% cashmere sweaters  Little patterned dress: Go for a good fit, and a good zipper  Denim jacket: Look for one with a plain look, not too distracting  You can look in the menâ€™s section too for an oversized fit/look  Leather jacket: Large armpit area, length that ends at the waist, less flashy hardware is good for people who wear gold jewelry   Black purse: Good material, interesting hardware, easy to open/easy to wear

A tip for Canadians: I try to thrift practically everything I can, because I'm fortunate enough to live like 10 minutes away from a huge Value Village and like 5 other thrift stores, but I have had an impossible time finding good "Mom Jeans" at any thrift store. So I actually bought some from Bluenotes and they are such good, sturdy jeans. I've never had an actual pair of jeans (not jeggings) from Bluenotes tear in the thighs or crotch. A lot of the other clothes aren't always amazing in quality; they're pretty on par with places like Forever 21 but the jeans themselves are, in my experience, always good quality.   **Side note: If you're like me and you worry about buying from ethical retailers, I will say Bluenotes has a 3/5 star ethical rating because the materials used to make the clothes are not always acquired from ethically produced suppliers, but to the best of my knowledge (I could be sorely wrong but I did research them, though it's a little difficult to find information on Canada based retailers), they produce the garments themselves through ethical labor.

Personally I think having  well made leather shoes and take good care of them is the best with the smallest Co2 footprint. Not having so many leather products that maintaining them is a hassle. Beads of sweat appeared on the leftist's forehead, his sallow complexion quickly turning as white as the Klan robes I have in my closet. He violently threw his hands to his ears in a futile attempt to block out the facts and logic erupting from my mouth.  "... ISM!"  With a blood-curdling scream, the leftist's veins bulged, a hollow wail rising from deep within him. With a fantastic cry, the leftist's head burst apart, raining blood and grey matter throughout the pub.  Marveling at my handiwork, I quipped "I guess you should have moved to Venezuela."  As I walked out of the pub, a cacophony of applause and raucous laughter echoed behind me. Just another day's work.

I think the main takeaway from most closet essential videos - including this one, is to find a good fit for your body! Even spending lots of money on an item like a pair of jeans is worth it because you know it'll last long. And when it fits you well, you're likely to feel confident in it, want to wear it more often, and be able to pair more outfits with it. That's good value for your buck!   Some more criteria that Ashley mentioned: - Longevity, materials and its quality, COMFORT (for shoes too), the silhouette of the piece that is flattering for YOU, attention to detail (hardware, stitching, etc)   And even functionality of a piece may be important, like how you can easily access your purse, or slip on a pair of shoes, even that body suit she mentioned.    All of these tips aren't meant for you to exactly go out and buy yourself a leather jacket or a frilly top if you aren't into it -- use those criteria's to make your own! For Madewell bring in an old pair of jeans you want to get rid of (any brand) and they'll give you a 20 dollar discount on a new pair! If you wait until they have store-wide sales and use this discount the jeans get way more affordable (and you get to recycle your denim instead of throwing it out! Yay sustainability!)

Honestly I'm more picky with my jeans than with what I put on my hair and I'm the type to overanalize ingredients and squat in the same alley trying to decide what to buy for hours.  That being said, I don't trust what they write about fabric content. 100% cotton won't feel the same every time no matter if we're talking about cotton used for jeans or t-shirts.   I like my jeans thick and stuff but no to the extent even hulk wouldn't rip it because they don't sit nicely on my body. Still, they need to have decent amount of strength or else they will look bad after two months. The other type of jeans is thick but very stretchy jean but it's so fuckin rare you could break your legs trying to find one pair. I swear they don't change their shape at all for years and always look like new, even in knee and crotch area. I have no idea what they make them from but this type of fabric is my holy grail. They're magic. I've only menaged to hunt down two pairs of these jeans so far ğŸ˜– well, at least it's something c:  And jogging jeans are shitty. They look horrible after first wash and are unflattering and urghhh. So many things were done wrong with them.
